AYN Thor Qualcomm Sensor Core data

The sensor registry inputs in this directory were recovered from the stock
AYN Thor Android BSP. They select the Kailua HDK SH5001 profile while leaving
runtime and learned calibration state writable under /userdata.

Stock Android build: Thor_V1.0.0.377_20260206_165408_user
Stock ADSP family: ADSP.HT.5.8-01329-KAILUA-1
Hardware platform: HDK
SoC ID: 603 (QCS8550)
Physical IMU: Senodia SH5001

The split adsp.mdt/adsp.bXX and adsp_dtb.mdt/adsp_dtb.bXX payloads are taken
from the same stock Android vendor partition. The generic Odin 2-family ADSP
image boots on Thor, but it does not contain the SH5001 driver.

Runtime path
------------

The ADSP/QSH firmware owns the SH5001. hexagonrpcd exposes the QSH file
services, libqmi/libssc receives SSC reports over QRTR, and ssccli provides a
raw accelerometer/gyroscope smoke test. The generated registry and learned
per-unit data live under /userdata/system/qcom-sensors/thor and are never
overwritten automatically.

The stock registry requests sns_tppe.so as a dynamic DSP sensor library, so
that one stock payload is supplied under dsp/adsp. The other Android FastRPC
and sensor HAL helper libraries are not needed for the basic SSC stream.

The SM8550 device tree enables Thor's stock ADSP firmware and the upstream
ADSP FastRPC channel with SensorsPD/PDR routing. The channel remains a
qcom,non-secure-domain and normally appears as /dev/fastrpc-adsp. Forcing it
to the secure-only /dev/fastrpc-adsp-secure node allowed the listeners to open
but did not make the stock SensorsPD publish its SSC QMI service.

S27qcom-qrtr starts qrtr-ns before any SSC client lookup. S28qcom-sensors then
generates the registry with the stock HDK/603 filters, starts SensorsPD before
RootPD, and prefers /dev/fastrpc-adsp (with the secure node retained only as a
fallback). Both listeners are supervised because their FastRPC nodes disappear
temporarily during an ADSP or SensorsPD restart. Sensor startup waits for the
AYN Thor ALSA card so audio finishes binding to the shared ADSP before any
sensor FastRPC session is opened. S28 publishes a readiness marker only after
both FastRPC supervisors are alive; S29 will not expose the DSU bridge without
that marker.

Motion bridge
-------------

S29qcom-motion exposes the built-in accelerometer and gyroscope as DSU/Cemuhook
slot 0 on 127.0.0.1:26760. Configgen enables the source for Azahar, Cemu,
Dolphin, Eden, Ryujinx and Yuzu only while the bridge readiness marker exists.
The bridge is supervised and automatically restarts after a transient SSC,
ADSP, or process failure without leaving a stale readiness marker.

The initial Thor coordinate profile maps the stock SH5001 landscape stream into
the console DSU frame. Cold-boot startup, raw streaming, stationary gyro zero,
DSU delivery, concurrent AYN Thor audio and supervisor recovery have been
validated on Thor hardware. Moving-axis tests also confirm that lowering the
left and right edges produces opposing lateral acceleration and gyro roll with
the expected DSU polarity. Emulator-side sensitivity still varies by emulator
and game.

Run `batocera-qcom-motion --check` for a DSU packet check, or
`batocera-qcom-sensors-test 5` to validate the complete sensor stack.

Calibration
-----------

Launch "Odin 2 / Thor Sensor Calibration" from the Tools system with the Thor base
resting still. The guide zeros the gyroscope and then automatically captures
five base orientations, so no button press is needed while balancing the
clamshell on an edge and the controls never need to face down. The resulting
full 3-axis correction compensates offset, gain, and sensor mounting angle.
The launcher and its image are installed in the persistent Tools directory and
are refreshed on Thor boots so existing userdata installations receive updates.
Calibration is stored in
/userdata/system/qcom-sensors/thor/motion-calibration.ini.
